result.execSummary:
The defendant Camara L Hamilton was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Retail Theft - Intentionally Take (<=$500) [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.50(1m)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Camara L Hamilton in court with attorney Terese M. Dick.  Defendant Camara L Hamilton in custody.  Michael Jerome Lonski appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: KAR.
Case calendared for plea and sentencing hearing.  State advised the Court they have complied with the Victims' Rights Law.  Negotiations placed on the record by the state.

AS TO COUNT 1: Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to her plea, advised of her Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Plea questionnaire, addendum and jury instructions, received and filed. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the criminal complaint and ordered a judgment of conviction be entered on the record. Defendant further advised that if she is not a US citizen deportation is possible.

Court sentences defendant to serve 120 days in the House of Correction with credit for 120 days, a TIME SERVED DISPOSITION.  Due to defendant's financial status, Court will waive costs, fees and surcharges.

Defendant advised of appeal rights.

Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief and Pretrial Incarceration Credit, received and filed.
